fields.description:
We created the MARS project with key MARS. However, the API request is failing when we try to fork. We&#x27;ve tried to understand the API documentation listed here https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Busername%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/forks

However, the Request Example doesn&#x27;t specify what the key names should be and in what order they should be in. Nothing really says that we should be posting a keyed object with name "project" it just says "all Of". So we are making assumptions on how the API should work.

Any help is greatly appreciated, see the request URL and post body along with the error message returned from the API.

https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/myteamname/initial-index-ui/forks

*This is our post body*

{code}
{
    "name": "my-repo-temp121211",
    "owner": {
      "username": "myteamname"
    },
    "is_private": true,
    "project": {
		"key": "MARS"
	}
}
{code}

*Fails with error*

{code}
{
    "type": "error",
    "error": {
        "message": "Invalid project"
    }
}
{code}

When a code snippet is added in the list, the correlation of numbers break, and the next number always starts in 1. To reproduce the issue, this is what&#x27;s in the README.md and it&#x27;s not rendered correctly:

{code}
#!python
1. Text of point 1.
2. Text of point 2.
{code}

// javascript code\\
3. Text of point 3.

{code}


{code}

It seems that currently, once you access your account&#x27;s "Projects" tab under:

{code}
#!python

https://bitbucket.org/dashboard/projects 
{code}

The projects displayed are only those you have Admin access to, and not all you&#x27;re working on (read/write access).\\
Would be better having all these projects displayed at once to improve the management of the same.

Workaround: For now, the user needs to access the Team&#x27;s page and then its projects to see those they have only read or write access.
